#loading the movies file
movies = spark.read.option("Header", "true")\
        .option("multiline", "true")\
        .option("escape", "\"")\
        .csv(file_movies)
#transformations for movies
## dropping irrelevant columns
cols_to_drop_movies = ['overview', 'revenue', 'tagline']
movies = movies.drop(*cols_to_drop_movies)

##extracting from relase_date column the year
movies = movies.withColumn('release_date', substring('release_date', 7,9))

##extracting necessary information from the structured columns
columns = ['genres', 'production_companies', 'production_countries', 'spoken_languages', 'cities']
schema = ['array<struct<id:int , name:string>>',
              'array<struct<name:string, id:int>>', 
              'array<struct<iso_3166_1:string , name:string>>',
              'array<struct<iso_639_1:string , name:string>>',
              'array<string>']

for column, field in zip(columns, schema):
    movies = movies.withColumn(column, from_json(col(column), lit(field)))

movies = movies.withColumn('genres', movies.genres['name']).withColumn('production_companies', movies.production_companies['name'])\
    .withColumn('production_countries', movies.production_countries['name']).withColumn('spoken_languages', movies.spoken_languages['name'])\
    .withColumn('spoken_languages', array_remove('spoken_languages', "?????")).withColumn('spoken_languages', array_remove('spoken_languages', "??????"))\
    .withColumn('spoken_languages', array_remove('spoken_languages',''))

Part 2 - Data Analysis¶

We will analyze the distribution of users by city and understand their behavior (regarding querying for movies and ordering tickets for movies).¶

Insights:¶

  1. We want to know what is the percentage of users in each city that are searching movies that are available in certain cities (For example, we can note that users from Eilat searched only for movies from Eilat) - it helps us divide the movies according to what the users are searching the most.
  2. We examined the percentage of queries that users from Eilat were looking movies by actors and we found out that no one was searching by actors in their query - we can remove the actors column from Eilat.

  3. We checked the percentage of queries that users from Jerusalem were looking for movies by actors and we found out that they are heavily looking for movies by actors (users from Tel Aviv, Kibuts Gesher and Haifa searched for it 50% of the queries - we think it's also a lot), and they search especially for:

    • Johnny Depp
    • Brad Pitt
    • Tom Hanks

  4. We examined the percentage of queries that users from Haifa were looking for movies by directors and we found out that more than 91 percent of Haifa's queries contain a search by director.

  5. We examined the percentage of queries that users were looking for production countries and we found out that users from Eilat, Kibuts Gesher and Jerusalem are always searching for movies accroding to the countries it was produced in(users from Haifa and Tel Aviv significantly less).
  6. We checked what users from certain city are searching for movies in Hebrew and we found that more than 85 percent of Jerusalem's queries got the Hebrew language while the other queries are less than 1% - Therefore, we would like to put the films that are available in the Hebrew language in Jerusalem.
  7. We checked what users from certain city are searching for movies that were produced in Israel and we found that users from Jerusalem are searching for it significantly more than users in other cities.
  8. We checked for each location what is the oldest year the users searched for - for Tel Aviv and Haifa is 2010, for other is 1990. Therefore, the oldest year users searched for is 1990.
  9. We examined the production companies that users were looking for and we found out that users from Eilat are searching for it significantly more than users in other cities.
  10. We examined the genres that users were looking for and we found out that users from Tel Aviv are searching a lot by the "Action" genre, users from Haifa search a lot b the "Drama" genre and users from kibuts Gesher search a lot by the "Family" and "Documentary" genres

Optimizer:¶

  1. We made an optimizer that calculates the average amount of entries in each field sort and separated by residents of each city. This is used to find the most optimized way to sort and secondary sort database (allowing binary search and minimizing amount of repeat big searches).

We will start by answering the following questions:¶

  1. What is the percentage of users in each city
  2. What is the number of queries in each city, the number of ticket buying - Comparison of distributions
In [15]:
#question1
def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return '{p:.2f}%  ({v:d})'.format(p=pct,v=val)
    return my_autopct

users_per_city = users.groupBy("user_location").count()
df = users_per_city.toPandas()
city_count = df['count'].to_list()
cities = df['user_location'].unique()
colors1 = ["#bb99ff", "#99ff99", "#ff9999", "#99d6ff", "#ffbf80"]
plt.pie(city_count, labels = cities,autopct=make_autopct(df['count']),
        explode = [0.05 for _ in cities], radius = 1.7, colors = colors1)
plt.title("Percentage of users in each city", fontdict={'fontsize': 23}, y=1.3)
plt.show()

With the help of this pie we can see the distribution of users by city.¶

  • For example, it can be seen that most users live in Jerusalem

#question2
users_per_city = users.groupBy("user_location").count()\
.withColumnRenamed("count", "number_of_users")
tickets_location = tickets.join(users, tickets.user_id == users.user_id)
tickets_by_location = tickets_location.groupBy("user_location").count()\
.withColumnRenamed("count", "number_of_orders")
queries_location = queries.join(users, queries.user_id == users.user_id)
queries__by_location = queries_location.groupBy("user_location").count()\
.withColumnRenamed("count", "number_of_queries")
queries_tickets_location = queries__by_location.join(tickets_by_location,\
queries__by_location.user_location == tickets_by_location.user_location)\
.drop(tickets_by_location.user_location)
queries_tickets__users_location = queries_tickets_location.join(users_per_city,\
queries_tickets_location.user_location == users_per_city.user_location)\
.drop(queries_tickets_location.user_location)
df = queries_tickets__users_location.toPandas()
colors2 = ["#ff99e6", "#ffad99", "#bb99ff"]
ax = df.plot(kind='bar', x="user_location", figsize=(18,5), color=colors2)
plt.title("Percentage of users, queries and tickets buying in each city",\
          fontdict={'fontsize': 23}, y = 1.1)
plt.xlabel("City", fontdict={'fontsize': 14})
plt.ylabel("Amount", fontdict={'fontsize': 14})
for p in ax.patches:
    width = p.get_width()
    height = p.get_height()
    lst = [5288, 21652, 30873, 24839, 17348]
    lst2 = [24411, 99942, 139679, 112802, 81706]
    if height in lst:
      x, y = p.get_xy() 
      ax.annotate(f'{height/queries_location.count():.3%}',\
                  (x + width/2, y + height*1.02), ha='center')
    elif height in lst2:
      x, y = p.get_xy() 
      ax.annotate(f'{height/tickets_location.count():.3%}',\
                  (x + width/2, y + height*1.02), ha='center')
    else:
      x, y = p.get_xy() 
      ax.annotate(f'{height/users.count():.3%}',\
                  (x + width/2, y + height*1.02), ha='center')
  
plt.show()

We can see that:¶

  • There is an identical distribution in each city between number of users, number of queries and number of tickets buying.
    • For example, there are 30.62 percent of users who live in Jerusalem, 30.462 percent of the ticket buying were made by them and 30.873 percent of the queries were made by them.

actors_by_jerusalem = queries_user.groupBy("user_location","actors").count().\
sort(col("count").desc()).\
filter(queries_user['user_location'] == "Jerusalem").\
drop(queries_user.user_location).withColumnRenamed("count", "Number_of_queries")
searched_actors_by_jerusalem = actors_by_jerusalem.\
where(actors_by_jerusalem.actors != "[]").groupBy().sum()
not_actors_by_jerusalem = actors_by_jerusalem.\
where(actors_by_jerusalem.actors == "[]").drop(actors_by_jerusalem.actors)

df_not_actors_by_jerusalem = not_actors_by_jerusalem.toPandas()
c = df_not_actors_by_jerusalem['Number_of_queries'].\
to_list() + df_searched_actors_by_jerusalem['sum(Number_of_queries)'].to_list()

print("Top 5 languages searching:")

for c in each_cities2:
            lan_amount = queries_location.filter(queries_location.user_location.contains(c)).select('lang').rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x[0][1:-1].split(', ')).countByValue().items()
            sortedd=[]
            for l in lan_amount:
                sortedd.append(l)
            sortedd.sort(key=lambda x: x[1] , reverse= True)
            print()
            print(f"Users from {c} searched for:")
            print(sortedd[0:5])

#insight6
queries_location = users.join(queries, users.user_id == queries.user_id)
queries_location_hebrew = queries_location.select('lang', 'user_location').\
where("lang like '%עִבְ%'")
queries_location_hebrew_1 = queries_location_hebrew.groupBy("user_location",\
"lang").count().sort(col("count").desc())
queries_location_hebrew = queries_location_hebrew_1.groupBy("user_location").\
sum("count").sort("sum(count)").\
withColumnRenamed("sum(count)", "number_of_hebrew_searching")

        xticks = range(0,28000,1000))

plt.ylabel("City", fontdict={'fontsize': 14})
plt.xticks(rotation=40, horizontalalignment="center")
plt.show()

  • Users from Haifa search a lot b the "Drama" genre (how we do not have enough drama from the wild boars?).
  • Users from kibuts Gesher search a lot by the "Family" and "Documentary" genres

Optimizer:¶

  1. Calculates the average amount of entries in each field sort and separated by residents of each city. This is used to find the most optimized way to sort and secondary sort database (allowing binary search and minimizing amount of repeat big searches).
In [30]:
#optimizer1
queries_location = queries.join(users , users.user_id == queries.user_id)
each_cities2=['Eilat', 'Jerusalem', 'Tel Aviv', 'Haifa', 'Kibuts Gesher']
column_select = ['genres', 'lang', 'actors', 'director', 'country', 'from_realese_date', 'production_company','user_location']
column_to = ['genres', 'lang', 'actors', 'director', 'country', 'from_realese_date', 'production_company']
twoD_dic = {}
for c in each_cities2:
    twoD_dic[c] = {}
    df_c = queries_location.select(column_select).filter(queries_location.user_location.contains(c))
    tot = df_c.count()
    for coll in column_to:
        twoD_dic[c][coll] = tot
def func(x):
    if x == "[]":
        return 0
    return x.count(',') + 1
funcc = f.udf(lambda x: func(x))
queries_1 = queries_location.select(column_select)
for c in column_to:
    queries_1 = queries_1.withColumn(c, funcc(c))
printt = {}
for city in each_cities2:
    printt[city] = []
    for c in column_to:
        resu =queries_1.filter(queries_1.user_location.contains(city)).select(c).rdd.map(lambda x: (1, int(x[0]))).reduceByKey(lambda x, y: x + y).collect()
        resu=resu[0][1]
        printt[city].append(
            f"{c}:{round(resu/twoD_dic[city][coll],2)}")
for city in each_cities2:
    print(f"Users from {city} search in an average query :")
    for p in printt[city]:
        print(p, end=" ,")
    print("\n")

We can see that:¶

  • Like #insight3, No one from Eilat searched for movies by actors, therefore we got 0 as average.
  • We need to remember that one search can have more than one entry. For example, 0.89 does not mean that 89% of the queries of users from Tel Aviv include search by actors (in #insight4 we saw it's 50.46%)
